1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,013
This is a short walkthrough of the trial-risk early-warning dashboard.

2
00:00:04,313 --> 00:00:16,398
The idea is simple: catch the risk that a trial might have to stop — early, and across three levels: the individual participant, the study as a whole, and the client relationship.

3
00:00:16,698 --> 00:00:22,331
It runs on a hybrid of cloud Claude (under a BAA) and on-device local models.

4
00:00:22,631 --> 00:00:27,463
And throughout, the AI only detects, aggregates, and triages.

5
00:00:27,763 --> 00:00:30,586
It never makes the safety or termination call.

6
00:00:30,886 --> 00:00:32,908
Let me show you how it works.

7
00:00:33,908 --> 00:00:38,068
Early-phase trials can stop for reasons that build up quietly.

8
00:00:38,368 --> 00:00:40,356
A participant's safety signal.

9
00:00:40,656 --> 00:00:44,036
A cohort's toxicity creeping toward the stopping rule.

10
00:00:44,336 --> 00:00:46,870
Or a sponsor going cold on the program.

11
00:00:47,170 --> 00:00:54,994
The trouble is that the first formal look is often the cohort review or a governance meeting — and by then we are days or weeks behind.

12
00:00:55,294 --> 00:01:02,166
The dashboard watches all three of these continuously, so the earliest mover is visible long before that meeting.

13
00:01:03,166 --> 00:01:05,142
Here is the dashboard itself.

14
00:01:05,442 --> 00:01:16,653
Three panels — participant, study, and client — each with a simple red, amber, green status, the top signals underneath, and the engine that powers it.

15
00:01:16,953 --> 00:01:19,741
Below the panels is a live early-warning feed.

16
00:01:20,041 --> 00:01:30,933
Right now everything is amber: a candidate liver signal on one participant, an enrollment limit breached at the study level, and a payment-aging flag on the client side.

17
00:01:31,233 --> 00:01:39,682
Each panel rolls its signals up to a status — but that status is a prompt for a human, not a verdict the system reaches on its own.

18
00:01:40,682 --> 00:01:47,391
The participant tier is the most sensitive, so it runs entirely on-device, with zero egress.

19
00:01:47,691 --> 00:02:02,427
It flags candidate dose-limiting toxicities inside the evaluation window: Hy's-Law liver signals, QTc prolongation, PK exposures beyond the safety margin, and escalating adverse-event clusters.

20
00:02:02,727 --> 00:02:04,023
The key word is early.

21
00:02:04,323 --> 00:02:10,444
It surfaces the pattern and pre-assembles the safety-committee packet before the formal cohort review.

22
00:02:10,744 --> 00:02:13,706
What it does not do is adjudicate the toxicity.

23
00:02:14,006 --> 00:02:17,276
That is the medical monitor and the Safety Review Committee.

24
00:02:18,276 --> 00:02:34,912
The study tier watches the trial's trajectory against its own rules: the cohort toxicity rate against the stopping rule, enrollment and screen-failure limits, the safety quality-tolerance limits from ICH, and central data-quality signals.

25
00:02:35,212 --> 00:02:44,893
These are de-identified, aggregate numbers, so they run on cloud Claude — with any participant-level drill-down dropping back to the on-device model.

26
00:02:45,193 --> 00:02:50,881
The project manager owns these calls, with the safety committee on anything safety-related.

27
00:02:51,881 --> 00:02:58,973
The third tier is the commercial one — the early warning that a sponsor might cancel, de-scope, or not renew.

28
00:02:59,273 --> 00:03:07,969
Payment aging, a drop in communication, scope-reduction change orders, and the sponsor's own financial and pipeline health.

29
00:03:08,269 --> 00:03:12,737
This is non-sensitive business data, so it sits on cloud Claude.

30
00:03:13,037 --> 00:03:15,861
And I want to be clear about what this tier is.

31
00:03:16,161 --> 00:03:20,645
It is decision-support for the account team, surfacing signals.

32
00:03:20,945 --> 00:03:24,267
It is never a judgment the system makes about a sponsor.

33
00:03:25,267 --> 00:03:30,285
Underneath, one rule decides where everything runs: sensitivity.

34
00:03:30,585 --> 00:03:37,588
Participant-level safety and unblinded data go to the on-device model, and never leave the validated environment.

35
00:03:37,888 --> 00:03:45,309
Non-sensitive, aggregate operational and commercial data go to cloud Claude, under a business-associate agreement.

36
00:03:45,609 --> 00:03:48,258
And here is the rule that governs the whole thing.

37
00:03:48,558 --> 00:03:56,429
The AI flags, aggregates, triages, and drafts the alert — it never makes the safety or termination call.

38
00:03:56,729 --> 00:04:01,592
The reported numbers come from the validated safety database, never the model.

39
00:04:01,892 --> 00:04:09,360
Every flag triggers a human review and a logged disposition, and nothing is paused or terminated by the system itself.

40
00:04:10,360 --> 00:04:13,702
There is an optional advanced layer for teams that want it.

41
00:04:14,002 --> 00:04:19,368
Instead of waiting for a threshold to be crossed, it watches for drift and surprise.

42
00:04:19,668 --> 00:04:27,785
Optimal transport measures how far a distribution has moved from a learned reference, in a way that respects clinical severity.

43
00:04:28,085 --> 00:04:39,895
Active inference treats the monitor as a model of the expected trajectory, so rising surprise is itself an early warning — and it can even recommend the most informative next test to run.

44
00:04:40,195 --> 00:04:51,877
It is decision-support only: the threshold rules stay authoritative, the methods were independently checked, and it is validated and frozen before it ever informs a regulated decision.

45
00:04:52,877 --> 00:04:54,674
Here is how it comes together.

46
00:04:54,974 --> 00:04:59,921
Day nine of cohort four: a participant's labs post a Hy's-Law pattern.

47
00:05:00,221 --> 00:05:10,005
The on-device model recognizes it, and because it is inside the evaluation window, flags a candidate toxicity — without any data leaving the device.

48
00:05:10,305 --> 00:05:17,400
Within minutes it assembles the case and routes it to the medical monitor and the committee chair, ahead of the scheduled review.

49
00:05:17,700 --> 00:05:25,211
The humans take it from there: a confirmatory test, the committee convenes, dosing pauses per protocol.

50
00:05:25,511 --> 00:05:26,981
The payoff is the timing.

51
00:05:27,281 --> 00:05:36,034
This surfaced on day nine, not at the cohort meeting on day twenty-one — with the packet already built, and a human making every call.

52
00:05:37,034 --> 00:05:38,463
Building it is staged.

53
00:05:38,763 --> 00:05:51,217
First, the safe wins: wire the study and client tiers from existing operational and commercial feeds into cloud Claude, behind a human-review queue, with de-identified data only.

54
00:05:51,517 --> 00:06:00,398
Second, the on-device participant tier in the validated environment, with the safety logic encoded and alerting wired to the medical monitor.

55
00:06:00,698 --> 00:06:11,364
Third, the scoring, escalation, and audit trail — and, optionally, the advanced engine, validated and frozen before it informs anything.

56
00:06:11,664 --> 00:06:14,022
Each phase delivers value on its own.

57
00:06:15,022 --> 00:06:21,788
So, in one line: catch termination risk before the meeting, and let humans make every call.

58
00:06:22,088 --> 00:06:26,572
It is earlier — a liver signal on day nine, not day twenty-one.

59
00:06:26,872 --> 00:06:28,999
It is three tiers on one screen.

60
00:06:29,299 --> 00:06:38,519
It is governed by design — sensitive data on-device, validated tools owning the numbers, and the committees and project managers deciding.

61
00:06:38,819 --> 00:06:47,123
And it fits the program: a phase-one pilot deliverable on the same hybrid stack — no new principle, just a new target.

62
00:06:47,423 --> 00:06:48,742
Thanks for watching.
